          "body": "Verses 17-18 are as detailed as any ancient land conveyance document: 'Ephron's field… the field and cave which was in it, and all the trees which were in the field, that were within all the confines of its border, were deeded over to Abraham for a possession in the presence of the sons of Heth, before all who went in at the gate of his city.' The legal comprehensiveness is intentional. Archaeologists studying Hittite land-transaction documents (the Hittite Laws, §§46-47) note that purchasing the full field with its trees created a more robust and incontestable class of ownership than purchasing a cave alone. Abraham's insistence on the full field (23:9) is not sentimentality — it is legal strategy. Every named detail (the trees, the borders, the gate, the witnesses) renders the deed unambiguous and irrevocable. Calvin comments: 'Abraham wished to have a fixed habitation for his posterity in that land which God had promised.' The legal precision is the permanent marker of the promise: the cave of Machpelah will bear Abraham's name in the deed until the promised land is finally distributed to the twelve tribes."
