          "title": "The burial — faith's first foothold",
          "body": "After eighteen verses of grief, negotiation, and legal process, the narrative arrives at the act that began it all: 'Abraham buried Sarah his wife in the cave of the field at Machpelah facing Mamre (that is, Hebron) in the land of Canaan' (23:19). The burial is the chapter's emotional and pastoral center, but it is also a theological statement. Sarah is the first of the patriarchs to be laid to rest in the promised land. Every subsequent burial at Machpelah — Abraham (25:9), Isaac, Rebekah, Leah, Jacob (49:29-32; 50:12-13) — repeats the faith-statement: we belong to this land, and this land belongs to us, by promise, by purchase, and by the faithfulness of the God who called us out of Ur. Hebrews 11:39-40 reflects on the patriarchs: 'all these, having gained approval through their faith, did not receive what was promised, because God had provided something better for us.' The cave at Machpelah is a monument to promise-sustained faith: the patriarchs held the down payment while the deed of the whole land awaited the fullness of time. In that sense, Sarah's burial is an act of corporate confession — 'we will be here when God fulfills what He has sworn.'"
