        "excerpt": "I am a stranger and a sojourner among you; give me a burial site among you that I may bury my dead out of my sight.",
        "body": "Abraham's self-identification in verse 4 is the chapter's interpretive key. He calls himself a ger ve-toshav — a stranger-and-sojourner. The pairing is not mere rhetorical doubling. Ger (alien, foreigner) describes someone without native legal status. Toshav (resident-alien) describes someone who lives among a people but holds no ancestral claim to their land. Together they name Abraham's legal and social position among the Hittites: he has lived in their vicinity for decades, commands extraordinary respect (23:6), but holds no title to any of their land.\n\nThis self-identification is not false humility. It is the theological engine of everything that follows. Because Abraham is a stranger-and-sojourner, he cannot simply bury Sarah anywhere in Canaan — he must request, negotiate, and purchase. And because he is a stranger-and-sojourner who holds a promise that this land will one day belong to his descendants, he cannot accept a borrowed Hittite grave. The ger-and-toshav identity creates the need for a purchased possession (achuzzah) in precisely the land God has covenanted to give.\n\nThe Hittites' response in verse 6 is strikingly generous and strikingly revealing. They call Abraham a 'prince of God' (nasi elohim) — the ESV translates 'mighty prince,' the NASB 'mighty prince,' but the Hebrew places elohim before nasi, which most commentators read as a superlative: 'a prince among the greatest.' Their offer — bury your dead in the choicest of our graves, none of us will refuse you — is genuine hospitality. But it is precisely what Abraham cannot accept. A Hittite grave for Sarah would mean Sarah rests in ground that will revert to Hittite ownership when the generous offer-giver dies. Abraham needs a legal title, not a social courtesy.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ger* — from the root gur, to sojourn. The ger is a protected category in later Mosaic law (Leviticus 19:33-34; Deuteronomy 10:19) — Israel must love the stranger because they were strangers in Egypt. *Toshav* — from yashav, to dwell; a resident-alien. *Nasi elohim* — 'a prince of God' or 'a godly prince'; the superlative construction with elohim is common in Biblical Hebrew (cf. 'a great city,' Jonah 3:3, lit. 'a city of God')."
